{"key":"processedPost-9248038","value":{"id":9248038,"first":9247983,"last":9248048,"when":1226764567,"utime":"11/15/08 05:56 PM","content":"That is the recipe if you're using calcium carbonate.&nbsp; If you're using hydrated lime(which I recommend) use it at a starting rate of 1 teaspoon per cup of peat.&nbsp; Your after hydration pH will be in the 8 to 9 range, and within 24 hours will drop to around 7.5 to 8.<br /><br />If you used one cup of hydrated lime per 15 cups of peat, that's too much.&nbsp; I'd double the peat and measure pH again.&nbsp; Be sure to let it sit for an hour or two before measuring.&nbsp; In addition, if you'll add up to ten percent gypsum, it will bring the pH down a tad also.<br />RR","title":"Re: Casing Soil Question","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}